Observation Details: Seen beyond ice flow to the north in vicinity of other loon and GBBG, near the giant scaup raft. Noted black back of neck and sharp demarcation of line between neck and white throat. Didn't note chin band, unfortunately. Posture seemed hunchier, neck seemed thicker - the opposite of a delicate COLO seen nearby. Known bird, continuing. Later spotted again in same vicinity, with other more experienced birders. Discussed this bird with Avery Fish, who also saw it later, and then again later on close-up at DAR.

Known bird, continuing. Spotted previousl in same vicinity, but closer, and again here with other more experienced birders. Discussed this bird with Avery Fish, Allan Strong, and Jim Mead. Mentioned I saw the chin-strap to Jim Mead; on second thought, I'm not sure I did. Avery also saw this bird later, and then again later on close-up at DAR. Would've liked closer look. Lifer.

Observation Details: Large flock moving frequently, foraging in weedy field then flying in circles before settling back down. Counted 10, then multiplied to estimate 50. Estimated 7 multiples of 50. One exceedingly pale bird, likely the “angel” Common Redpoll photographed by others at this site.

Estimate by tens than fifties of large, constantly moving flock. I’ll add and attempt to count from photos. Searched carefully for HORE, though neither of the two paler birds I noticed were seen well enough to rule out CORE. Flushed by the arrival of the RTHA; flock flew west over treeline beyond the farm.
